twenty years of neoliberal economic policies have yielded disappointing results for developing countries . 
latin america , the region with the most tried to put in place the proceeds of the " washington consensus " ( free market price deregulation , privatisation ) , has been the experience of weak growth and volatile widening inequalities . 
among the former socialist economies of eastern europe and the soviet union , few have reached the real output levels that prevailed before 1990 . 
in sub-saharan africa , most economies failed to respond to the adjustment programs demanded by the imf and world bank . 
the rare examples of success occurred in countries that have followed their own pace and which are not really a false prospectus of neoliberalism . 
china , vietnam and india : all three violated virtually all the rules in the neoliberal guidebook , even when they moved in a geared more to the markets . 
it is now time to abandon neoliberalism and the washington consensus . 
but the challenge is an alternative , a set of policies to promote the development without falling into the trap of a new plan unworkable , supposedly for the well-being of all countries without distinction . 
experience suggests that an adequate growth program must be rooted in two strategies : an investment strategy designed to kick-start growth in the short term and a strategy of implementation of institutions designed to provide an economy with resilience in the face of economic shocks . 
the key to investment strategy is to achieve interest to the local businessmen to the local economy . 
encouraging foreign investment or liberalizing everything and then wait until the situation improves is not viable . 
an effective strategy must achieve two objectives : to encourage investment in non-traditional areas and pruning the projects or investments that fail . 
for this , governments must use both the carrot and the stick . 
find out what a country produces ( or could produce ) easily is the main challenge of economic development . 
the carrot is needed because there is much to win socially if you discover , for example , that cut flowers , the soccer balls , or computer programs can be produced cheaply . also because this knowledge can guide the investments of other entrepreneurs . 
the businessman who made the first " discovery " can capture only a small part of the social value that this knowledge generates , and quickly , it is followed on this path by others . 
as a result , entrepreneurship of this type ( discover what can be produced ) is usually under-supplied in the lack of commercial incentive . 
we must also use the stick to ensure that these incentives do not lock unproductive and wasteful investments . 
the establishment of such a strategy may vary from one country to another , according to the administrative capacity , the prevailing incentive regime , the flexibility of the tax system , the degree of sophistication of the financial sector and the underlying political economy . 
the funding programmes time limited , the funding of public companies and the financing of exports represent some ways to approach for this , but there are many others . 
there is no single instrument will work everywhere . 
governments that do not have the capabilities required to exercise their leading role of the private sector are going right to the disaster and have little chance of improving the allocation of resources . 
this attempt can succeed , but economic growth requires more than the temporary resuscitation of investment and entrepreneurship . 
it also requires effort to build four types of institutions needed to maintain growth momentum and the strengthening of the resistance to shocks : 
the institutions to build the market ( right of ownership and contract law ) 
the institutions of market regulation ( outsourcing , economies of scale , and professional information ) 
the institutions market stabilisation ( monetary and fiscal management ) 
the institutions to legitimise the market ( social protection and insurance ) . 
building and solidifying these institutions , however , takes time . 
enjoy an initial period of growth to experiment and innovate on these fronts can be high dividends in the future . 
the key point here is that institutional arrangements are , by necessity specific to each country . 
find out what works in any one country requires experimentation . 
after all , the institutions are not plants capable of being planted in any soil and climate . 
the reforms that operate in an environment can be weak or faltering in others . 
such specificity helps explain why successful countries ( china , india , south korea and taiwan , among others ) combining unorthodox elements to policies . 
it also explains why large institutional differences persist among the industrialised countries of north america , western europe and japan in areas such as the role of the public sector , the legal system , corporate governance , the financial markets , the labour markets and social protection . 
while economic analysis can help to make institutional choices , public deliberations and the collective choice also have an important role to play . 
in fact , we can think of participatory democracy as méta-institutions which will make a choice in the " menu " of institutional arrangements in each area . 
designing such a growth strategy is both more difficult and more easily than the establishment standard neoliberal policies . 
more difficult because the constraints that it needed to growth are often specific to each country and adapt well to standardized recipes . 
but it is easier because once these constraints , clearly objectivées relatively simple policy changes can yield a lot from an economic point of view and pave the way for a virtual circle of growth and institutional reform . 
adopt this approach does not mean abandoning standard economic thinking , far from it . 
neoliberalism is to neoclassical economics as astrology is to astronomy . 
in both cases , it takes a lot of blind faith to move from one to the other . 
critics of neoliberalism should not oppose the classical economy but only its misuse . 
