the real cost of the iraq war 
in life , the most important things , like life itself , have not price . 
but this does not mean that the issues involving the preservation of life ( or a way of life ) , such as defense , should not be subjected to cold economic analysis and rigorous . 
shortly before the current iraq war , when larry lindsey , the economist of the bush administration , has suggested that the cost could be between $ 100 and $ 200 billion , other officials quickly demurred . 
for example , the office of management and budget director mitch daniels put the figure at $ 60 billion . 
it now appears that lindsey 's numbers were grossly underestimated . 
worried that the bush administration can be misleading everyone on the cost of the war in iraq , as it has done on weapons of mass destruction and its links with al qaeda , i agree with linda bilmes , a budget expert at harvard , to examine the issue . 
even we who are opposed to the war , were appalled by what we have discovered : our estimates , modest to moderate , vary a bit less of a trillion dollars to more than $ 2 trillion . 
our analysis starts with the $ 500 billion that the congressional budget office openly talks about , which is ten times higher than what the administration said the cost of the war . 
its estimate is wrong at this point because the figures announced do not even include the full budgetary costs to the government . 
and the budgetary costs are a fraction of the costs of the entire economy . 
the bush administration , for example , has done everything she could to hide the large number of veterans who are severely wounded : 16 000 for the moment , which more or less 20 % with serious brain and head injuries . 
so it is no surprise that its figure of $ 500 billion ignores the shortcomings and the costs of health that the government will have to pay over the next few years . 
the administration does not face the problems of military recruitment and retention . 
the result is the payment of bonuses to those who commit to new , more benefits and higher recruiting costs : an increase of 20 % just between 2003 and 2005 . 
in addition , the war is extremely wearing equipment , which he will have to replace a part . 
these budgetary costs ( without taking into account the interests ) amount to $ 652 billion in our conservative estimate and $ 799 billion for our moderate estimate . 
we can assume that as the government has not reduced other expenditures or increased taxes , these expenses were funded by debt , and the cost of interest on that debt would add $ 98 billion dollars ( conservative ) to $ 385 billion ( moderate ) to the budgetary costs . 
of course , the biggest burden of injuries and deaths is borne by the soldiers and their families . 
but the military pays disability benefits that are much lower than the value of lost earnings . 
similarly , payments for soldiers killed only amount to $ 500 , 000 , which is far below the standard estimates of the economic cost of a death life , sometimes referred to as the statistical value of a life ( of 6,1 to 6,5 million dollars ) . 
but the costs do not stop there . 
the bush administration once proclaimed that the war in iraq would be good for the economy , and a spokesman has even suggested that it was the best way to ensure low oil prices . 
as is often the case , things have turned out differently : the oil companies are the big winners , and the american and global economies have lost . 
being extremely conservative , we believe the overall effect on the economy if only 5 or $ 10 of the increase is attributed to the war . 
at the same time , money spent on the war could have been spent on something else . 
we believe that if a part of that money had been invested in roads , schools , and research , the american economy would have been stimulated more in the short term and its growth would have been higher in the long term . 
there are a number of other costs , some potentially important , which are very difficult to quantify . 
for example , the americans are paying $ 300 billion annually for the " option value " of military preparedness , which allows them to be prepared to fight where it matters . 
the fact that americans are willing to pay this suggests that this potential value exceeds the costs . 
but there is little doubt that she has been greatly diminished and will remain for several years . 
in short , even our " moderate " estimate can significantly underestimate the cost of the us commitment in iraq . 
and our estimate does not include any of the costs involved in the huge losses of life and property in iraq . 
we are not trying to explain that the american people were deliberately misled about the costs of the war , or that the bush administration 's gross underestimate must be put on the account of incompetence , as it vehemently argues is in the case of weapons of mass destruction . 
we are not trying to judge whether it was more cost-effective ways to make war . 
recent evidence that the number of deaths and injuries would have been considerably reduced if we had better body armor been provided to soldiers show how the economies in the short term can lead to long-term costs . 
it is undeniable that when the programming of a war is a matter of choice , as was the case here , inadequate preparation is even less justifiable . 
