the moral of capital punishment . 
the us is often criticized for their refusal to abolish the death penalty . 
many now claim that the abolition of the death penalty is a necessary condition to establish a civilized system of criminal law . 
the nobel peace prize winner gary becker is not this opinion . 
european governments are resolutely opposed to the death penalty -- the european union banned completely , and some europeans consider its use in the united states barbaric . 
in fact , many european intellectuals argue that the death penalty , and punishment in general , does not deter criminals . 
but , while europeans , with crime rates well below those of the united states in the last half-century , could long afford some " soft " in most of the crimes , they have seen their crime rates increase sharply over the past 20 years . 
on the contrary , american rates have fallen , partly thanks to greater use of punishment . 
the death penalty . 
i am for the execution of some people convicted of murder because , and for that reason alone , i believe that it deters other murders . 
if i did not believe that , i would be opposed to capital punishment , because revenge and other possible motives should not be a basis for public policy . 
serious empirical research on death penalty in the united states began with a study of isaac ehrlich , published in 1975 in the american economic review . 
some studies that have followed have sometimes found a much weaker deterrent effect , others a much stronger effect . 
however , the information available are quite limited , so one should not base its conclusions solely on the econometric evidence . 
of course , public policy in terms of punishment cannot expect the evidence is perfect . 
but even with the limited quantitative evidence available , good reasons to believe the deterrent power of capital punishment are sufficient . 
most people , and murderers in particular , are afraid of death , especially when it follows swiftly and almost the commission of a murder . 
as david hume about suicide , " no man has ever rejected life , while it was worth living . 
this is our natural horror of death ... " similarly , schopenhauer believed that " when the horrors of life reach the point where they exceed the horrors of the death , a man puts an end to her life . 
but the terrors of the death considerable resistance ... " 
opponents of the death penalty often proclaim that the state has no moral right to take anyone 's life , including that of the most reprehensible murderer . 
yet it is absolutely the wrong conclusion for who believe that the death penalty is a deterrent . 
to see why , suppose that for every murderer executed ( instead of , say , to be sentenced to life in prison ) , the number of murders is reduced to three , which is a much lower number than ehrlich and other estimates of the deterrent effect . 
this means that for every murderer not executed , three innocent victims would die . 
in fact , the government " would take " indirectly many lives if it did not use the death penalty . 
save three innocent lives for every person executed seems like a very attractive , and even two lives saved by execution seems like a cost / benefit ratio persuasive in favour of the death penalty . 
admittedly , however , the argument in favour of capital punishment becomes less clear-cut when the number of lives saved each execution falls . 
but even if only one life were saved each execution , the market can still be desirable if life saved is much better than the life removed , which is usually the case . 
many people object to compare the qualities of life spared and the deleted . 
yet i do not see how to prevent such a comparison . 
take the case of a career criminal wheel and killing a victim who led a decent life and left several children and a partner behind it . 
suppose it would be possible to save the life of an innocent victim in executing such a criminal . 
it seems obvious to me that save the life of such a victim must carry more weight than taking the criminal 's life . 
of course , all the cases are not as clear , but a comparison of the qualities of individual lives must be part of any reasonable social policy . 
this is also why the death penalty should be used only for murder and not for lesser crimes . 
when it comes to choose between taking lives and , for example , reduce the property theft , the thesis of more lenient punishment is much more powerful . 
although serious assaults , including some gruesome rapes , are sometimes the murders in severity , and could possibly call the death penalty , i am not for its use in this type of case . 
one of the main arguments for reserving capital punishment for murders is " marginal deterrence . " 
if the attacks were punished by the death penalty , this would bring the attackers to kill their victims for not be discovered ( which is a major reason for the severity of the punishment is proportional to the seriousness of the crimes ) . 
one of the complications may be , however , that a murderer fight harder to avoid being captured , which could lead to more deaths . 
but , although marginal deterrence is important , i believe that the resistance of murderers to their capture , sometimes at the expense of their own lives , is really indirect evidence that criminals fear the death penalty . 
of course , the risk of executing innocent people that worries me . 
my support for capital punishment would weaken much if the rate of killing of innocent people was as important as many claim . 
however , i believe that the appeal process in the united states offers enormous protection , not so much against wrongful convictions against wrongful execution , which means that there is very little , if any , cases of people executed for which it is proved that they were innocent . 
and this situation has been strengthened enormously with the development of dna identification . 
i say again that the debate about the death penalty is a debate on the deterrent power ( which may be reduced by lengthy appeals ) . 
i can understand that some people are skeptical about the evidence , although i think they are wrong about this , and the common sense of the problem . 
it is very disturbing to take someone 's life , even a murderer , but sometimes highly unpleasant actions are necessary to prevent even worse behavior causing the death of innocent victims . 
