turkey 's efforts to impose fines and prison sentences to those who toe the official line convinces me that i was right to oppose the opening of negotiations on the country 's accession to the european union . 
in december 1999 , the european council granted turkey candidate status of the eu , which meant that turkey will enter the union at a future date has not yet set . 
then the council asked the european commission to decide before october 2004 if turkey met the necessary political criteria for membership , which include democracy , the rule of law and respect the right of ethnic minorities . 
this decision has been one of the last taken by the commission of romano prodi , of which i was a member . 
among its 30 members , 29 said that turkey had fulfilled the criteria sufficiently to be able to continue . 
i was the lone dissenter . 
this is the report of the commission on turkey , prepared by günter verheugen , then in charge of the enlargement of the eu , which has driven my decision . 
this report mentioned that in 2003 some 21 , 870 turks have asked for asylum in the eu , of which 2 127 have been accepted . 
in other words , the eu governments themselves acknowledged in 2003 that the turkish government had persecuted over 2 000 of its own citizens . 
in the meantime , the commission published a progress report on turkey believing that reforms were continuing , although at a slower pace , under the mildly islamic-minded government of prime minister recep tayyip erdogan . 
this report was nevertheless state serious doubts : human rights violations , including torture , continued ; the military 's influence remained too high ; freedom of expression was not universally observed ; non-muslim religious and cultural minorities were victims of discrimination and violence against women was not sufficiently strong opposition . 
the situation has not changed much since accession talks began in october . 
beyond the persecution pamuk is currently the victim , the unacceptable behaviour abound . 
in march 2005 , the police violently intervened in a demonstration marking international women 's day . 
in may , the largest teaching union has been banned for having supported the education of 14 million kurds in turkey in their own language . 
it is undeniable that intolerance reached to the heights of the turkish government . 
foreign minister abdullah gul has recently cancelled sharply a press conference in copenhagen when he spotted a kurdish journalist in the audience that the danes have refused to get out . 
such acts and attitudes amply justify my disagreement in october 2004 . 
but even if these shortcomings were corrected , turkey should not be admitted to the eu , because this is not a european country . 
christianity , feudalism , the renaissance , the lights , democracy and industrialization have made us what we europeans are , but they have not made turks what they are . 
so i am not convinced that reforms in turkey implemented at the insistence of the european commission would continue after accession . 
i suspect that there will be backsliding . 
in addition , turkey 's accession would surely to that of ukraine , belarus and moldova , and perhaps of georgia , armenia and azerbaijan . 
the first three of these countries are certainly more european than turkey . 
leaving aside the three caucasus republics but including the successor states to yugoslavia , this would give an eu of some 35 members . 
what kind of union would that be ? 
the eu is not simply a club of friends . 
it is based on freedom of movement of goods , services , capital and people . 
the commission as guardian of the union treaties , must protect these four fundamental freedoms , which means that it must sometimes persuade , and if necessary force , member states to change their laws . 
the policies on alcohol in sweden , the volkswagen-law in germany , and discrimination against foreign investment funds in france are examples of cases that have made the commission unpopular . 
but they were necessary . 
by the time i left the commission , i was sitting on a pile of 1 , 500 of irregularities of this style . 
in short , eu accession means accepting incisive measures that deeply affect the internal affairs of a state . 
it will be impossible with such disparate members . 
the eu would fall victim to what the historian paul kennedy calls " imperial overreach . " 
it is unacceptably diluted . 
it is for this reason that the former french president valéry giscard d 'estaing feared that the entry of turkey does not lead to the end of the eu , and that is why the former german chancellor helmut schmidt said : " the accession of turkey would be more than the eu could bear . " 
