short-term interest rates are surprisingly low : only 2 % in the euro zone , just 1 % in the us , and zero in japan . 
the expansionary monetary policy has been a success , but only after pushing interest rates to historic lows and have convinced investors that borrowing costs will remain at their current levels for a long time . 
the monetary stimulus has mainly been to increase asset prices : everything that produced a benefit , a dividend or a rent becomes much more attractive , and so much more valuable in financial terms , when interest rates are very low and should stay . 
this explains the large gaps between current prices of real estate in the us , equities in new york , london and frankfurt , and long-term bonds around the world and what should be , conventionally , their core values . 
that will happen when central banks start to raise interest rates ? 
in 1994 , the increase in interest rates in the short term has led to an increase in long-term rates ( and lower prices long-term bonds ) to at least double that laid down by the standard models this year . 
interest rates on developing peripheral economies have also risen much more than the rates of the main advanced industrial countries . 
the first danger for 2005 and for years to come , when global interest rates rise , as is likely , is another wave of financial crises of emerging markets . 
for countries such as mexico , brazil , turkey , argentina , korea , malaysia and thailand , the record of the 1990s shows that interest-rate spreads can grow and capital flows reverse remarkably quickly , regardless of how favorably the representatives of the imf and analyses by major banks view a country 's policies . 
interest-rate spreads of emerging markets are currently abnormally low . 
international money flows , aside from inflows into the us , are not yet at levels associated with a " irrational exuberance , " but there is unlikely to happen before interest rates start to rise . 
this is an alarming prospect , because if there is a lesson to learn of the 1990s , it is that nobody should overestimate the stability of international financial flows . 
the second danger comes from the high asset values in the main advanced industrial countries . 
the dominant mode of thought within the federal reserve , which i fully support , argues that the revolution of information technologies continues , that potential production in the united states is growing always very quickly and that the output gap is thus relatively wide . 
this implies that interest rates will certainly remain low for a considerable time . 
in addition , the trust in the federal reserve is high , and the last remnants of the premium of the risk of inflation of the 1970s wrung out of interest rates . 
therefore , even after output levels income to their potential , interest rates will remain low by the standards of the 1980s and 1990s . 
all of this is , of course , good news for all those who hold assets such as bonds on the long term , equities and property . 
indeed , the rising prices of active on the long term was precisely what aspired lowering interest rates : making bondholders and especially homeowners richer , after all , provides a boost to spending . 
but the bad news is that even if interest rates are expected to remain low for some time , they will not stay as low indefinitely . 
the important thing is that when interest rates rise , asset values will fall . 
it is during these periods , and particularly when asset values fall quickly and significantly , that we discover the full level of competence of our central bankers in their main task : reducing financial volatility and promoting economic stability . 
it is also during these periods that we discover how individuals who hold long-term bonds , real estate , or stocks have not because they think that the current prices are attractive relative to basis , but because their prices have risen in recent years . 
it is a crucial issue for policy makers , because those who have bought long-term assets because the price seemed to increase indefinitely are also those who will sell as soon as the trends seem to be reversing . 
in particular , the us trade deficit heralds a mass instability in cases where the asset prices in the long term should fall significantly . 
it is certain that the challenges facing the world 's economic policy makers over the years will be different from those that they have faced since the collapse of the illusion of the nasdaq . 
the risks associated with inflation are probably less dangerous than those generated by a fall in production and the threat of deflation . 
but , as we learned during the 1990s , this does not mean that the challenges of the future will be easier to solve . 
