the islamic identity 
everywhere you look at the present time , islam is used ( and misused ) as a political force . 
some muslims use them as incentives to action ; many muslims in the west ( and in other countries ) perceive it as an " other " and a " containment exclusion . 
as a turk , i feel directly these two sides of the debate . 
the reason that islam is a religion of the " other " to western eyes is that the west has witnessed a systematic de-institutionalisation of religion . 
this is not the religion that has disappeared from modern western life , of course , but rather the claims that religious institutions can make on individual behavior . 
religion in the modern world is more personal and spiritual experience than ever before . 
however , a process of de-institutionalisation of religious experience is also taking place within islam . 
the politicisation of islam is displacing the authority of islam 's religious classes , the ulema . 
as in the west , islamic religious experience becomes more personal . 
the interpretation of religious texts by individual muslims , including political activists , intellectuals and women , is a consequence , among many others . 
there is also the dissemination of religious knowledge , the teachings of the koran being abused and taken out of context to support political objectives . 
who now decides what is legitimate and what is illegal in islam ? 
who has the authority to interpret religious texts ? 
who can issue a fatwa or declare " jihad " ? 
nowadays , activism and terrorism provide , or rather , a source of legitimacy . 
it is thus that lay people decide what does or does not mean islam , without the authority of religious schools and specialized training . 
indeed , islam today is primarily interpreted by political actors and cultural movements , not religious institutions . 
this de-institutionalisation has enabled islam to move the status of local and national social bond to creator imaginary ties between all muslims around the world who feel oppressed or displaced . 
thus , islamism can unite members who were deeply divided : sufis and muslims previously saints ; shia and sunni muslims ; conservative saudi arabia and iran revolutionary . 
islam is also dynamic , its believers leaving rural areas for cities , including the cities of the west . 
many see this movement as negative and point out that these people are socially uprooted and that they are shifting in alienation and , for some , terrorism . 
but social mobility is also a precondition for creating a modern outlook . 
of course , the migration is creating a sense of distance among muslims , if not a complete break , with their social origins . 
so their religious experience is new , deprived of theological , community , or state institutions . 
religious experience instead becomes a form of social imagination within which they reconstruct a sense of belonging to islam in an environment that is new and strange . 
this is not the distance from modern life , but the proximity to it that triggers a return to religious identity . 
indeed , the vast majority of radicalism is evident in the groups which , by their experience of mobility and displacement , are familiar with secular western ways of political thinking and urban living . 
confused by an unknown , these individuals are clinging to islam becomes their only support . 
but for that support works , islam must be liberated from its traditionally subservient attitude , passive and docile in the face of modernity . 
by wearing a veil or beard , claiming the right for places to pray at work or school and demanding special foods , muslims identify themselves openly as muslims . 
they are telling the world that they are more zealous and meticulous in their religious observance that individuals who confine their religiosity to privacy . 
for example , non-muslims usually see veiling as a sign of the debasement and inferiority of muslim women . 
shame , however , it has become for muslims a sign of their positive affirmation of an islamic identity . 
young muslim women in europe illustrate this transformation perfectly . 
girls who adopt the headscarf in french and german schools are closer in many aspects ( namely , the youth culture , awareness of fashion and the language ) , their classmates that their mothers uneducated who are forced to stay at home . 
in adopting the headscarf for the european public sphere , these girls are unwittingly the symbol and the role of muslim women . 
this trend goes well beyond headscarves . 
all western muslims possess a double sense of belonging , a double cultural capital . 
they define themselves by their religiosity , but they have also acquired universal , secular knowledge . 
the fact that they have a double cultural capital , they can move relatively freely between different activities and spaces ( home , school , houses of young and urban leisure space . 
being a muslim and being an islamist are two different things . 
we are seeing today is the change of a muslim identity to an islamic identity . 
the religious self for individual muslims is being shifted from the private to the public realm . 
the question for everyone is whether this quest for identity can be satisfied with headscarves and wide public acceptance of islamic religious practice , or if a positive affirmation of islam requires a more fundamental renunciation of modernity . 
