the iranian debate on iraq 
no country in the middle east is monitoring the events of the postwar iraq as closely as iran . 
the geographical proximity , an intense and bloody history of war with saddam hussein 's iraq , religious and emotional connections with the shia from iraq , some concern about the united states and its policy in the region : these are the son that unite iran to its western neighbor . 
given ongoing tensions with america , iran is particularly concerned by the possibility of a continuing us presence in its neighbour , as well as by america 's dominant role in building the future of post-saddam iraq . 
outsiders may find it difficult to follow internal iranian debates , but they exist , they are intense , even if they are not always visible to the wider international public . 
you can reach three general approaches in the evolving iranian debate on post-saddam iraq . 
iranian pragmatists argue that iran will inevitably have to cooperate with the united states in post-saddam iraq , even if only to ensure that the rights of the shiite population of iraq are respected . 
for this reason , iran should win assurances that the new iraqi leader will not be hostile to it , and will seek friendly bilateral relations . 
other key considerations for the pragmatists include preserving iraq 's territorial integrity and the repatriation of tens of thousands of iraqi refugees living in iran . 
they are moderates who think that the iranian government should urge the united states to obtain the extradition of members of the mujahdin-e khalq organisation ( mko ) , as well as the total dismantling . 
in exchange , the iranian government should offer its support to ensure peace , stability and security in iraq . 
in sum , the pragmatists would limit us-iran relations , focusing on a programme that largely reflects iran 's domestic concerns . 
in general , the conservative forces of iran support this approach . 
another approach is proposing a more active role and cooperative for iran in the reconstruction of iraq . 
defenders of this position argue that iran is well placed to facilitate the reconstruction , because of its well-established infrastructure of personal and institutional ties with iraq . 
finally , we think , the united states and the international community will recognize the value of iranian cooperation . 
iranian cooperation should be rewarded by the dismantling of the mko infrastructure in iraq , perhaps in exchange for an iranian commitment to address the activities of al qaeda , as well as to expel members of al qaeda to iran . 
above all , iran should ask americans to respond to its cooperation with the assurance of a guarantee in return that iran does not become the target of american military action . 
in short , the defenders of cooperation call for an open market and explicit : iran 's support for stability during the current phase of transition as well as its commitment to maintain cooperation relations with all permanent government emerges in iraq , in exchange for the improvement of the regional and international position of iran . 
this position is widely shared among iran 's reformers , within and outside the government , as well as by the technocratic class and business is more international . 
finally , for iran 's radicals , the possibility of cooperation with the united states is pure fantasy . 
they are convinced that america is bent on undermining iran 's security and endanger its national interests . 
according to the radicals , the united states will at the very least seek to impose significant changes in iranian foreign policy . 
at worst , they argue , america will seek to impose regime change in iran in an active way . 
it will actively work against the acquisition of nuclear knowledge and energy by iran and could even try to weaken the military capacity of iran in its entirety . 
the radicals perceive the american invasion of iraq as a reflection of america 's desire to encircle iran . 
in return , they believe that iran must take an aggressive stance in defending its interests , forming strategic alliances with russia and other regional powers , and using iranian influence in iraq to prevent the formation of a government pro-american and anti-iranian in baghdad . 
