democracy on the nile ? 
the surprise decision by egyptian president hosni mubarak to propose a constitutional amendment allowing the direct and competitive presidential elections could very well be a giant step for democracy in egypt and in the arab world . 
westerners accustomed to a pluralist democracy can be difficult to understand what a potentially huge shift this decision will result in a country accustomed to military rule for more than 50 years . 
under the current system , egyptian citizens can only show up on the day of a presidential referendum every six years to say yes or no to the only name on the presidential ballot . 
this explains why someone such as mubarak has always received more than 90 % of the vote , albeit in the middle of indifferent turnout . 
syrian and iraqi strongmen have done even better with this system , probably because they demanded that the names and addresses of voters to be placed at the bottom of each ballot . 
many people have long argued that democratization in the middle east will not move until egypt is fully engaged in the process . 
egypt could not truly engage on a path of democratization without first amend its constitution , that in order to reduce the pharaonic powers of its president and limit the length of his term . 
mubarak , after all , is already in his 24th year as president . 
thus , his announcement of competitive presidential elections is an important first step . 
the regime may assume that it will be able to use the process to its advantage , but events may prove more difficult to control once people begin to feel empowered . 
