the envy of european dollar 
currencies can play a key role not only in commercial transactions , but also in the diplomatic and political wrangling . 
when this happens , commercial transactions become more difficult and subject to greater uncertainty . 
the politicization of money during the interwar depression was economically devastating . 
but violent currency wars took place more recently . 
during the 1960s , the international monetary order became the subject of a political tug-of-war . 
each side had quite different theories and explanations of on the situation . 
the europeans , especially the french , complained about what general charles de gaulle called " exorbitant privilege " of the us dollar . 
the general and his monetary guru , jacques rueff , argued that the us used the dollar 's status as a major reserve currency of the exchange rate regime of the bretton woods fixed in order to run deficits and pay for their overseas military adventurism ( at this time in vietnam ) . 
france responded by calling for monetary reform that would end the particular role of the dollar and tried to revive the largely discredited gold standard . 
the europeans began a long discussion of the advantages of monetary union , which would allow them to compete with the dollar . 
but from the american point of view , the international role of the dollar was a trap . 
other countries could change their exchange rates , and thus could maintain greater competition at the level of exports . 
the us government was powerless in the face of an undervalued yen , fueling the belief that the rest of the world used the dollar to attack america 's manufacturing base . 
the nixon administration has concluded that the only way to save the american economy was to engage in monetary unilateralism ( a monetary expansion so dramatic that other countries would be forced to adjust their exchange rates ) . 
these long-forgotten battles seem suddenly very present again . 
the world no longer has a fixed exchange rate regime , but the dollar remains the major reserve currency , a sort of floating bretton woods . 
for americans , the reserve role of the dollar is a potential threat while for non-americans , rather , it is another example of an american neo-imperial quest for hegemony . 
during this decade , china has taken the place of japan in the 1960s , preventing its exchange rate to rise in order to push export growth . 
this has been the target of us complaints about unfair competition , and efforts to impose an adjustment of exchange rates that would deter americans to buy toys , appliances and clothing chinese . 
american manufacturers have estimated that chinese-made bras constitute the american way of life . 
in the meantime , europeans ( especially the french ) complain about the huge deficits americans and de gaulle 's argument that the rest of the world is paying for the wars of america is back in fashion . 
some europeans suggest that asian central banks should hold a greater part of their reserves in euros , an echo of the general 's unsuccessful attempt to capitulate america in selling dollars for gold . 
the 1960s ended by a collapse of the " system " and by major financial turbulence , accompanied by an inflationary surge of commodity prices . 
everyone was hit and america 's role on the world stage has been shaken . 
a similar collapse at the moment should have a rather different effect . 
the floating-rate system of today is more stable and the adjustment costs distributed differently . 
the majority of americans do not suffer a lot of the dollar 's sharp fall because foreign sellers have to make adjustments prices for the american market . 
asian economies are growing vigorously and their central banks their rely on the united states . 
they should continue this policy not to see their export sectors to suffer a sudden setback on the american market capital . 
the united states will have more time to deal with a current account deficit that is unsustainable in the long term . 
the economically dynamic regions of the world ( north america and asia ) are linked by a pact that will ensure the continuity of the centrality of the us dollar . 
americans will continue to pile up debt because asians encourage them to do it . 
the repeal of the pact would be contrary to the interests of both parties . 
it is not an american unilateralism because the pact involves collaboration with asia . 
but for the europeans , who are excluded from the pact , it looks like monetary and economic unilateralism . 
in the meantime , the rise of the euro against the dollar suffered european industrial exporters . 
europe does not , however , able to relieve . 
indeed , europe will be the biggest victim of the new currency clashes . 
the responses predicted in the 1960s ( restoration of the gold standard or the invention of a common european currency ) seem more very useful . 
a single currency has not allowed to provide substantial protection . 
the old version of the european response ( what psychologists call " dollar envy " ) will only become more acute . 
the european central bank will be invited to extend the monetary base , as if the imitation of the dollar was the answer to all the industrial , structural , and demographic problems plaguing europe . 
but we should remember that europe 's problems do not come from currency manipulation . 
the protests against the new version of america 's exorbitant monetary privilege must be seen for what they are : a way to compensate for a real european powerlessness . 
so dollar envy is ready to end , and it is getting tougher , the international value of the dollar disappearing without any obviously bad effects on people who print and use it . 
an epidemic of policy 
the americans , as citizens of all the countries of the world , have come to accept the fact that the policy plays an important role in the appointment of certain kinds of public officials . 
few of us are surprised ( although some may be disappointed ) when a federal judge or a senior diplomat is appointed because he has managed a crucial test of loyalty to an important principle in the eyes of the party of the president or the prime minister . 
but science , in the view of all , occupies a special place and on this point , the united states is beginning to stand as a cautionary example for the rest of the world . 
scientific appointments must be based on objective criteria of training , competence and performance . 
clearly , it is legitimate to interrogate a future secretary of health and human services ( hhs ) on his views on abortion . 
but it is entirely out of appointees to sit in the scientific advisory committees to tests of political loyalty . 
similarly , membership of bodies examining the proposals scientists , a process that is fundamental to scientific progress , surely ought to be free of all the barriers that are unrelated to professional qualifications . 
unfortunately , scientists in the us are faced increasingly often these barriers . 
during the autumn of last year , the journal science has published several reporting on the issue . 
one was on the wholesale replacement of members of the advisory committee of the national center for environmental health , which is part of the center for disease control and prevention ( cdc ) , without consulting the center 's director . 
similar cases have also been observed in the advisory committee on lead poisoning and prevention , the cdc 's advisory committee on national human research protections , and the advisory committee on genetic testing . 
the current epidemic of ideology , in which the advisory committees are dissolved and reassembled with new members , and candidates are subjected to loyalty tests , seems outdated to some observers . 
the representatives of the hhs referred to it as a " fairly standard practice . " 
it is not a practice in america , or at least not until today . 
in all cases , the fact that the bush administration examines the candidates for key positions in order to determine their compatibility with its " values " is not really worrying . 
the most alarming development is on the level of importance of ideological investigations , which interfere in areas hitherto immune to this kind of manipulation . 
indeed , the most revealing in this political epidemic has perhaps a membership to the study section at the national institute of occupational safety and health , which assesses the subsidies to the study of the injuries occurred in the workplace . 
the advisory committees could be vulnerable to an occasional overhaul of this kind in the past . 
after all , they have recommended the policies that politicians will take into account . 
but study sections ? 
in october 2002 , science has published an editorial by david michaels and several of his colleagues . 
several of them were distinguished former officials who participated in some of the relevant committees and they brought a valuable perspective to the question , based on their personal experience . 
their article was a story in itself , but the consequences it had was even more interesting . 
it has unleashed a volley of letters in which scientists told of similar experiences . 
a muscular dystrophy research coordinating committee of the national institute of health told that an investigation had been conducted on it by a member of the white house . 
after having been asked about her views on various policies of the bush administration , none of them had to do with the work of the committee , she was asked whether she supports the president 's policy on embryonic stem cells . 
other person to be , a distinguished professor of psychiatry and psychology , reported receiving a call from the white house about his appointment to the national council on drug abuse . 
the caller said he had to do an investigation him to " determine whether his views could embarrass the president . " 
according to the professor , a series of questions followed , the representative of the white house keeping a rating . 
example : " you got two on three ; the president opposes needle exchange ( for intravenous drug users ) for moral reasons , regardless of the outcome . " 
then the conversation took a turn even more alarming . 
the official asked the nominee if he had voted for bush , and , having received a negative response , he asked : " why did you not supported president ? " 
this attitude is akin to a dictatorship , and not a democracy . 
the aim of scientific advisory committees is to provide advice , thoughtful in the political process . 
there is nothing to gain and much to lose , when a desired policy outcome is put forward . 
that is why the determination of research projects to support has always been a matter for objective peer review , not politicians . 
in fact , the law that applies here ( the law on the federal advisory committees , the federal advisory committee act ) requires explicitly that committees be impartial and " not inappropriately influenced by the appointing authority . " 
us secretary of health and human services tommy thompson and the white house personnel office should set an example to the rest of the world . 
they can do so very easily : within the law . 
