save the trees of life 
nobody can get through the day without using a by-product of the forest . 
to a greater extent than we normally believes , the paper on which you writing , water that comes out of our taps , the drugs that we are treating , the wood that our houses and furniture , all originate from the forest . 
forests provide the fresh air that we breathe and habitats of endangered species . 
they also provide us with recreational opportunities , which is becoming increasingly important in the complexity of our world . 
approximately 1,5 billion people living in the poor rural areas directly depend on forests for basic needs like food and firewood . 
yet deforestation continues . 
every year , we lose 14,6 million hectares of forest , or an area almost as big as four times switzerland . 
irresponsible forest management , enhanced by regulations and government bonds too weak , and the markets that reward illegal logging all conspire to deprive the world of its forests the most valuable and threatened . 
when the forests are beginning to disappear , a host of environmental , social and economic ills usually follow , affecting us all in one way or another . 
indonesia 's sumatra island is a good example . 
pulp and paper companies are driving a rampant and illegal destruction of forests that are home to the greater diversity of plants in the world . 
it is very likely that plants still unknown will disappear in the process as endangered species such as the rhinos and elephant , as well as the orangutan . 
when sumatra 's forests disappeared , entire communities will also be without proper place to live and no decent way to make their lives . 
in addition , the distortion that the trade in illegal products and cheap products needed to world markets is cause difficulties for responsible citizens . 
developing countries are losing $ 15 billion in tax revenues each year because of illegal logging . 
to make matters worse , the demand for wood for reconstruction following the tsunami of last year , has intensified a request already unsustainable on sumatra 's forests . 
the ponds in the amazon and the congo are the subject of similar threats . 
a recent study of the united nations , the millennium ecosystem assessment ( mea ) shows that the forests and other important areas are in serious decline due to mismanagement and will continue to disappear if serious measures are not put in place . 
information released by the brazilian government show that deforestation of the irreplaceable forests in the amazon , the fact of agricultural conversion , reached 2,6 million hectares last year , which is the total area of deforestation in the amazon to 17 % . 
but the battle against deforestation is not yet lost . 
various organisations , environmentalists and businesses worried about the state of the world 's forests are working together to reverse deforestation and improve the management of forests . 
so , for example , the world wildlife fund ( wwf ) and the world bank have helped the brazilian government to launch an initiative intended to establish new areas of forest protection over 17 million hectares in the form of national parks . 
the cooperation of the world wildlife fund and the world bank has also motivated partners to establish a trust fund to manage these protected areas in perpetuity . 
similarly , a meeting at the summit of leaders of the congo basin countries has enabled a cross-border cooperation on forest conservation and responsible management . 
all this has led to a $ 53 million initiative by the united states state department to promote congo forest conservation . 
since the first meeting of the leaders in 1999 , 3,5 million hectares of new protected areas have been organised in the congo basin . 
however , given the consequences of the asian tsunami last december , the weight of evidence provided by the mea and statistics on deforestation of the regions most critical , we must continue our efforts . 
the world bank and the wwf have recently promised to work for the reduction of 10 % of the global rate of deforestation for 2010 and work with the public and private sector institutions to allow ambitious achievements on forest conservation . 
wwf studies show that if the world 's forests are shared between different uses , including the protection of certain areas , the commercial management responsible and restoration forest landscapes , we can provide the world 's needs in forest products while maintaining important environmental and social values for the foreseeable future . 
business leaders , governments , civil society organisations must all play their role in achieving that vision . 
the saudis are fanatics ? 
the terrorist attacks in saudi arabia have led many to question the prospects of survival of the house of saud ruling and to consider the question of whether the kingdom is fundamentally dysfunctional and destructive or not . 
for one reason or another , it seems that saudi society has produced a stream of violent fanaticism that draws its inspiration from extreme religious orthodoxy . 
the fact that 15 of the 19 hijackers who took part in the september 11 , 2001 , attacks on the united states were saudis crystallized a perception of the kingdom as a bastion of authoritarianism and intolerance . 
in some respects , this perception is fair , but it cannot be applied to the saudi population as a whole . 
on the contrary , it would be a serious mistake to assume that fanatical islamism fully defines saudi attitudes toward religion . 
between 2001 and 2003 , i was part of a team to achieve a large-scale study of values in saudi arabia , egypt , iran , and jordan . 
our results have produced a surprisingly nuanced picture of saudi attitudes . 
by comparison with respondents in the other countries of the middle east , saudis were less religious overall , and their attitudes toward democracy and arranged marriages also indicate a moderate undercurrent . 
it is true that in the four countries , religiosity is widespread , more than 90 % of respondents collectively that they believe in god , in life after death , and in heaven and hell . 
but the saudis appear to be less religious than their fellow muslims . 
sixty-two percent of saudis described themselves as religious , compared with 82 % of iranians , 85 % of jordanians , and 98 % of egyptians . 
americans also appear to be more religious than the saudis , with 81 % . 
this variation can be explained in part by cross-national differences on the meaning of the term " religiosity . " 
for example , the americans can define religiosity differently than countries of the middle east , perhaps with a weaker attachment to religious beliefs in islamic countries . 
this might also account in part of the differences between the muslim countries . 
but the gap between saudis , on one side and the iranians , jordanians and egyptians , another in the self-defined religiosity , is so great that it would challenge the widespread perception of saudi arabia as a highly conservative and religious . 
indeed , the actions speak louder than words : only 28 % of saudis have said that they were attending weekly religious services , against 27 % of iranians , 44 % of jordanians , 42 % of egyptians and 45 % of americans . 
these conclusions , although contrary to popular perceptions of saudi culture , are less surprising than they appear . 
sociologists of religion have long argued that in a monolithic religious environment , or when religious institutions are closely tied to the state , the overall religiosity of the population declines . 
it makes sense to think that when state authorities enforce strict codes of behavior , people tend to rebel and move away from officially sanctioned religious institutions . 
little wonder , then , that egyptians and jordanians , who live in countries where the state does not enforce piety , are more religious than iranians or the saudis , who must cope with the police local " virtue " backed by the state . 
even on the issue of marriage , many saudis expressed surprisingly liberal views . 
the respondents were nearly evenly split on the question of arranged marriages , half supporting the idea that marriage should be based on parental consent , while 48 % preferred love as the basis of marriage . 
given the segregation of the sexes and paternal dominance firmly anchored , this result appears to reveal a strong desire for greater individual choice in what has traditionally been a family decision . 
finally , the saudis are supporters of democracy , once again contradicting a popular image of saudi conservatism . 
on the saudis polled , 58 % considered democracy the best form of government , 23 % disagreed , and 18 % have not spoken . 
the massive support for democracy in a country without secular and nationalist history seems counter-intuitive . 
in fact , support for democracy corresponds to several other liberal attitudes that we found in saudi arabia . 
supporters of democracy tend to be less religious , more secular , more tolerant of others , more critical of the actions of the public sector , and more concerned with western cultural invasion . 
beyond the survey data , history has shown that liberal ideas become more prevalent when a despotic monarch governs with the support of a religious institution . 
a strong current of liberalism appeared at the end of the ninth century in ottoman syria in response to the religious despotism of sultan abdulhamid . 
at the same time , an anti-clerical , secular movement on behalf of constitutionalism appeared in iran , in reaction to the absolutist alliance between the quajar shahs and the religious establishment . 
in view of the similarities between these historical precedents and current conditions in saudi arabia , we should not rule out the possibility of reform . 
data from the study also suggest that the saudis could very well demand a more transparent politics and a less interventionist religion . 
