the myth of humanitarian aid and trade 
humanitarian aid and trade became international buzzwords . 
more humanitarian aid ( including debt relief ) and better access to markets in rich countries to poor countries " products now appears to be at the top of the international agenda . 
in fact , the debate today is not about the measures to take , but on the quantity of measures to be taken , and how fast . 
lost in all this : the clear lessons of the last five decades of economic development . 
at the forefront of those lessons , we find that economic development is largely in the hands of poor nations themselves . 
the countries that have done well in the recent past have succeeded thanks to their own efforts . 
humanitarian aid and the markets played only a minor role . 
take the example of a developing country that has free and preferential market access to its bigger neighbour , which also happens to be the strongest economy in the world . 
suppose that this country is able to send millions of its citizens to work the other side of the border , receives a huge volume of foreign investment and is fully integrated into the international production chains . 
in addition , the country 's banking system is supported by its rich neighbour and its stated desire to act as a lender of last resort . 
globalisation could not come much better than this , is it not ? 
now consider a second country . 
it faces a trade embargo on the world 's largest market , receives neither foreign aid nor any form of support from the western world , is excluded from international organizations such as the wto and cannot borrow from the imf and the world bank . 
if these external disadvantages were not debilitating enough , you can add an economy that interview itself barriers against international trade ( in the form of state trading , import tariffs and quantitative restrictions ) . 
as the reader may have guessed , these are real countries : mexico and vietnam . 
mexico shares a long border 3,200 miles with the united states , which provides not only the privileged access to a market of goods and labor , but also to a share of the resources of the us treasury ( as the experience of the 1995 peso crisis has made the demonstration ) . 
by contrast , america has maintained its trade embargo against vietnam until 1994 , has not restored diplomatic relations before 1995 and has not granted the status most-favoured-nation to vietnamese imports that many years later . 
vietnam is still not entered the wto . 
now consider their economic performance . 
since the signing of nafta in december 1992 , the mexican economy has grown at an average annual rate of just over 1 % per head . 
this is not only far below the rates of champions of the asian economy , but it is also only a fraction of the performance of mexico 's own growth decades leading up to the debt crisis of 1982 ( 3,6 % per year between 1960 and 1981 ) . 
vietnam , however , grew at an annual rate of 5,6 % per capita since the onset of its economic reforms in 1988 and the restoration of diplomatic relations with the united states in 1995 and has continued to grow at a rapid pace of 4,5 % since . 
vietnam has witnessed a dramatic fall in poverty , while mexico has been a fall in real wages . 
these two countries experienced sharp international trade and foreign investment , but the picture is very different where it counts the most : in improving living standards , especially among the poor . 
what these examples show is that domestic efforts trump all other elements in the determination of the economic fortunes of a country . 
everything that the american market had to offer in mexico could not offset the consequences of policy mistakes on the internal market , especially the failure to reverse the real appreciation of the peso 's exchange rate or extend the productivity gains achieved in a narrow range of activities for export to the rest of the economy . 
what matters most is the adoption by a country the right growth strategy . 
without any advantage in mexico , vietnam has pursued a strategy focused on diversifying its economy and improving production capacity from local suppliers . 
the overall experience post-war that the domestic policies are what matter most . 
south korea took off in the early 1960s , not when foreign aid was at its apex , but when they began to seize up . 
taiwan has not benefited from foreign aid or privileged access to certain markets . 
china and india , the economic superstars of the moment , have prospered largely through their own reform efforts . 
it is tempting to foreign demand for their products for export the rare african successes , botswana and mauritius ( diamonds and garments , respectively ) , but it cannot go very far . 
of course , these two countries would be much poorer without access to foreign markets . 
but , as in all the cases of successful development , what distinguishes them is not the external advantages they possess , but their ability to exploit these advantages . 
it is enough to see how other countries have squandered the advantage that their purchase their natural wealth . 
the word " diamond " hardly conjures images of peace and prosperity in sierra leone . 
similarly , few of the export processing zones proliferating around the world have experienced the level of development that we observed in mauritius . 
it absolves rich countries of their obligation to help . 
they can make life harder for corrupt dictators , sharing more financial information and by refusing to recognise the international contracts that they sign . 
similarly , the increase in the number of workers from poor countries allowed to work in rich countries , and a wider range of growth-oriented policies by relaxation of the rules and wto conditions imposed by the united states would produce a greater impact on the long-term development . 
it is not proven that the expansion of access to markets and subsidies represents the best use of political capital of the northern hemisphere . 
the development should focus on improving the political environment in poor countries , rather than on aid and trade . 
