if the great argentine economist raul prebisch were alive today , he no doubt would wonder if the world is set to turn to the head . 
his theory hugely influential dependence argued that if poor countries relied too much on exports of raw materials , they would never achieve the industrial level needed to sustain rapid growth . 
they are ever-dwindling in a cycle of decline global commodity prices and reduced income . 
the answer prebisch favorite , protectionism , proved disastrous for the many latin american and african countries that have followed . 
but the fact is that for years , prebisch seems to have had the right commodity price trends over the long term . 
the efficiency gains in the areas of agriculture and the extraction of natural resources have lowers the prices of raw materials , especially in the 1980s and 1990s . 
with a few exceptions , countries that focused on commodity exports performed dismally , while the asian countries with only few resources have made rapid progress . 
today , however , with the asian giants , india and china , joining the global economy , the price of petrol , gold , wheat , and virtually every other raw materials are exploding . 
of course , there will always be cycles ( the price of oil , for example , will probably fall before they start rising again ) but the long-term trend of many commodities will clearly remain upward for some time yet . 
what many trade negotiators and other policymakers do not seem to have acknowledge yet , though prebisch would have understood immediately , it is that this dramatic turn of events has huge implications for the global balance of power . 
