lessons to be learned from the fiscal recklessness of america 
george w. bush has done more to destroy us economic policy that all the other presidents in american history , exceeding even his mentor , ronald reagan . 
in just three years in office , it has destroyed a fragile political consensus that had asked ten years of efforts and that could take another decade to be reconstructed . 
in doing so , bush has risked economic health and social stability in the long term of america . 
given that the long-term budgetary challenges that the us an extremely clumsy are not the only existing challenges , america 's fiscal blunders provide important lessons for other countries . 
the main problem with fiscal policy is that politicians can easily make themselves temporarily popular by cutting taxes and increasing public spending while running up massive public debts and leaving repayment to the future . 
this ploy can last a few years , but the budget deficits and growing public debt required earlier than scheduled a painful change of policy . 
yet a cynical politician can buy his re-election and perhaps be in retirement when the crisis coming . 
one would imagine that after decades of such episodes of fiscal irresponsibility in the countries of the world , voters would be allergic to this type of ruse . 
however , bush is doing it again , buying popularity today by doling out massive tax cuts while simultaneously increasing military spending , and spending on education and health . 
the result is a budget deficit equivalent to more than 5 % of gdp . 
worse still , the long-term budgetary outlook of america were already worrying before bush begins his reckless policies . 
the us population is aging , so that the costs of pension systems and health care financed by public funds will increase sharply . 
careful calculations show that the income that will be made available through the tax policies favored by bush may not achieve the tens of trillions of dollars that represent the costs of public pensions , health care and other fiscal spending expected by the population . 
at some point in the future , it will greatly increase recoveries taxes , drastically reducing public spending , or both , to compensate for the actions of bush . 
so why the population support his policies ? 
because it understands little these consequences on the long term , or that she cares little , even though they will eventually impact on the majority of americans . 
the richest taxpayers are , of course , happy because they received the bulk of the tax cuts . 
amazingly , the richest 5 % of us taxpayers received about half of the tax cuts , and these rich taxpayers clearly expect the other 95 % ( the middle class and the poor ) bear the majority of future spending cuts and tax increases . 
meanwhile , bush has convinced many poor and middle-class voters that they should be happy , too , without telling them that they will have to pay their small tax cuts with much larger cuts in future government services if his administration 's policies prevail in the long term . 
if the americans had a political memory , they would understand that they have already climbed this fiscal " roller coaster " over the last 20 years . 
ronald reagan also took office promising massive tax cuts and large increases in military spending . 
that ended a huge budget deficit by the mid-1980s . 
tax cuts made reagan extremely popular and have allowed him to be re-elected in 1984 . 
it then took over a decade ( starting in reagan 's second term until the terms of george bush , sr. and bill clinton ) to return to a budget surplus . 
of course , this result has need the approval of new tax increases , which has cost george bush , sr. his re-election and led to the polarized politics of the 1990s . 
the story is likely to be repeated . 
some right-wing ideologues in the bush administration believe that the budget deficits will ultimately a drastic reduction in social spending of the government . 
they hope to dismantle programs such as social security and medicare . 
but the american people strongly supports these social programs . 
the strategy which is first to cut taxes in order to lead subsequently mandatory cuts in social programs is doomed to failure and must inevitably lead to higher tax rates . 
others in the bush administration argue that tax cuts play a crucial role to pull the us out of recession . 
this argument is also wrong . 
america 's economy could recover without the tax cuts , and perhaps even more robustly . 
in all cases , it is a huge mistake to build long-term tax policies on the economic cycle in the short term . 
