calves , pigs and american democracy 
amidst all the headlines about the return of the democratic majority in congress after the november election , the result of an important election has gone largely unnoticed . 
although it has highlighted the shortcomings of the american political system , he has also made it possible to believe in the compassion of ordinary americans . 
in arizona , citizens can , if they have gathered enough signatures , submit a draft law to a direct popular vote . 
this year , one of the issues on the ballot was a law to prohibit pregnant sows , or calves reared for meat , tethering or confining in a way that prevents them from turning around freely , lie down or extend their members . 
those who do not know the factory farming may wonder why the need for such legislation . 
traditional farming , such that it applied everywhere in the world fifty years ago , and in some countries still today , allows animals to move and stretch . 
but now , almost 90 percent of the sows -- the mothers of the pigs reared and slaughtered for meat , bacon and ham -- spend most of their lives in stalls that measure about 60 centimeters by 2 , 2 metres . 
they can neither turn , their legs fully extended , or move forward or back more than a step . 
they are also kept on short tethers . 
in the same way , the calves are confined their lives in individual stalls where they cannot turn around , to sleep or stretch . 
for the most part , these methods are designed to save the cost of labor . they facilitate the management of animals and allow us to use less and less skilled workers . 
they also prevent the animals from wasting energy in moving around or fighting with them . 
a few years ago , following protests from animal welfare organizations , the commission of the european union has asked for a report to the standing committee of the eu on the methods . 
the conclusions of the report indicates that the animals suffer not able to move and boredom have nothing to do all day . 
of course , the simple common sense can come to the same conclusions . 
following the report , the eu has set the dates from which the confinement of farm animals will be banned . 
for calves , on 1 january 2007 . 
the stalls for sows , already banned in the uk and in sweden , will be banned from 2013 throughout the european union . 
measures to improve the welfare of laying hens , in battery cages with wire without enough room to stretch their wings , are also being gradually . 
in the united states , nothing of the kind is planned . 
previously , when my european friends asked me why the us accused such a delay in the welfare of animals compared to europe , i have had no answer . 
if they insisted , i had to admit that a possible explanation was that the americans care less about animals than europeans . 
then , in 2002 , animal welfare advocates put a proposal to ban sow stalls on the ballot in florida . 
to everyone 's surprise , the proposal was accepted by 55 percent of the voters . 
last month in arizona , despite well-funded opposition by the food industry , the ban containment of pens for veal calves and pigs has also been approved , by 62 percent of voters . 
neither florida nor arizona are particularly progressive states -- both voted for george w. bush over john kerry in 2004 . 
the results of these two votes strongly suggest that if all americans had to decide on the maintenance of pregnant sows and veal in containment , a large majority object . 
in the end , americans seem to care as much as europeans the living conditions of farmed animals . 
to explain the difference between the welfare of animals in europe and the us , it is without doubt compare the political systems . 
in europe , the concerns of voters about the living conditions of animals have found resonance among members of national parliaments and the european parliament , with the result the adoption of national laws and eu directives to improve their fate . 
in the us , by contrast , these same concerns have had no discernible effect on members of congress . 
there is no federal legislation on the welfare of animals and virtually no state legislation . 
because agribusiness my opinion , the tens of millions of dollars of the food industry pocketed by the representatives seeking to be re-elected is for something . 
the animal welfare movement , despite strong popular support , is not the weight in the arena of political lobbying and campaign donations . 
in us electoral politics , money matters more than the opinions of voters . 
party discipline is weak , and congressmen must themselves raise most of the funds needed for their re-election -- in this case , every two years for members of the house of representatives . 
in europe , where party discipline is strong and the parties , not the candidates , finance election campaigns , money plays a smaller role . 
in the united states , a country proud of its democratic tradition , calves and pigs are hardly the only losers . 
