celebration of the irrational 
hooray for the new nobel laureates in economy : daniel kahneman of princeton university , and vernon smith of george mason university in virginia . 
like many nobel prizes , these awards recognize not only the seminal work undertaken by kahneman and smith , but also the schools of thought that they have helped to develop . 
kahneman , a psychologist , has demonstrated that individuals systematically behave in ways less rational than traditional economists believe it to be . 
his research shows not only that individuals sometimes act differently standard economic theories predict , but also that they do it regularly , systematically , and in a way that can be understood and interpreted through different assumptions , competing with those used by the traditional economists . 
for most market players , and in fact , ordinary observers , this does not seem to make much difference . 
wall street brokers who peddled the actions that they know to be wrong exploit the irrationality that kahneman and smith have shown . 
a large part of the mania that led to the economy was based on the exploitation of the psychology of investors . 
in fact , this irrationality is not new for economists , either . 
john maynard keynes once referred to the stock market as not being based on rational individuals struggling to discover the foundations of the markets , but rather as a beauty contest in which the winner is the one who best guess what the judges will say . 
this year 's nobel prize celebrates the criticism of the market economy simplistic , like that of last year ( that i have received with two other colleagues ) . 
last year 's laureates emphasis on the fact that different market participants have different ( and imperfect ) information , and that this asymmetry of information have profound impact on the functioning of the economy . 
more particularly , last year 's laureates implied that the markets are not usually effective ; that there is an important role for government to play . 
adam smith 's invisible hand , the idea that free trade leads to efficiency as if by an invisible hand , is invisible in part because it is not there . 
this , too , is not news to those who work on a daily basis with the markets ( and make their fortunes by taking advantage of this information asymmetry and overcoming ) . 
for more than 20 years , economists have passionate for these so-called rational expectations " models " who assumed that all the players have the same information ( albeit imperfect ) and are acting perfectly rational , that markets are perfectly efficient , that there is never any unemployment ( except when it is caused by greedy unions or minimum wages imposed by the governments ) , and that there is never any rationing of funding . 
such models are dominant , particularly in postgraduate courses in the united states , despite all evidence to the contrary which show the triumph of ideology on science . 
unfortunately , students of these programmes of higher education today are the decision makers in many countries , and they are trying to implement programs based on these ideas , the so-called today market fundamentalism . 
let me be clear : the rational expectations models have contributed significantly to economic theory ; the rigor that their supporters imposed on economic thinking has highlighted the weakness of many underlying assumptions . 
good science recognizes its limits , but the prophets of rational expectations have generally shown little modesty . 
vernon smith is a leader in the development of experimental economics , the idea that you can test many economic proposals in a laboratory . 
one of the reasons that the economy is a subject if complex , which also explains the many disagreements among economists , is that economists cannot conduct controlled experiments . 
nature throws the real-life experiences , but in most circumstances , so many things change so quickly that it is often difficult to disentangle the causes of the consequences . 
in principle , in a laboratory , we can conduct controlled experiments , and therefore make more reliable inferences . 
critics of experimental economics worry that the subjects bring to experimental situations modes of thought determined outside of the experience , and that the experiences and the inferences are not as clear and that in the physical sciences . 
however , the economic experiments bring a certain knowledge of a number of important issues , such as the improved design of auctions . 
above all , the irrationality of market participants , the main issue of kahneman 's work , has verified repeatedly in the context of laboratories . 
one of the more amusing results by experimental economics is altruism and selfishness . 
it appears ( at least in experimental situations ) that experimental subjects are not as selfish that economists believe , except for one group : economists themselves . 
is it because the economy is a discipline attracts individuals who are , by nature , selfish or because the economy helps shape individuals making them more selfish ? 
the answer , surely , is a little bit of both . 
there is no doubt that the experimental research and the future work will resolve the question of the relative importance of these two hypotheses . 
the nobel prize shows just how important it is to study the individuals and economies as they are and not as we want to see them . 
it is only by understanding better actual human behavior that we can expect design policies that will also do better function our economies . 
