the roadmap of china 
china is about to adopt its 11th five-year plan , setting the stage for extend what is probably the most remarkable economic transformation of history , while improving the well-being of almost a quarter of the world 's population . 
never before has the world seen such sustained growth ; never before has there been such a reduction of poverty . 
the explanation of the long-term success of china is partly in its unique combination of pragmatism and vision of the future . 
while much of the rest of the developing world , following the washington consensus , is launched on a quest for higher gdp don quixote , china has once again made clear that it sought sustainable and more equitable increases in levels of real life . 
china realizes that it has entered a phase of economic growth imposing huge demands on the environment , which cannot last . 
at least to change trajectory , living standards will eventually be compromise . 
it is for this reason that the new five-year plan puts great emphasis on the environment . 
many of the more backward parts of china have been growing at a pace that marvel , were it not for the wonder if other parts of the country are growing even more rapidly . 
while this has reduced poverty , inequality has increased , with growing disparities between rural and urban areas , and between coastal regions and the interior . 
the report of this year 's world bank world development report explains why inequality , and not just poverty , should raise concern , and china 's 11th five-year plan tackles the problem head-on . 
the government has for several years talked about a more harmonious society , and the plan describes ambitious programs to reach that goal . 
china also recognises that what separates the least developed countries of the most developed countries is not only a disparity in resources , but also of knowledge . 
so it has laid out bold projects to reduce these disparities and create a basis for independent innovation . 
the role of china in the world and in the global economy has changed , and the plan also reflects this situation . 
its future growth will have to be based more on domestic demand than on exports , which means an increase in consumption . 
indeed , china is suffering from a rare problem : excessive savings . 
people save partly because of shortcomings in the programmes of social insurance of government : to strengthen social security ( pensions ) , public health and education will simultaneously reduce social inequalities , increase the sense of well-being of the citizens and promote current consumption . 
if this works ( and , so far , china has almost always surpassed even his own high expectations ) these adjustments may impose enormous pressure on a global economic system already destabilized by the enormous fiscal and trade imbalances united states . 
if china saves less -- and if , as officials have announced , it pursues a more diversified policy of investing its reserves , which will fund the trade deficit of more than $ 2 billion a day from the united states ? 
this is a topic for another day , but that day may not be far off . 
with such a clear vision of the future , the challenge will be implementation . 
china is a great country , which would not have been able to do so as well without widespread decentralization . 
but the decentralization raises problems of its own . 
greenhouse gases , for example , are global problems . 
while america says that it does not have the resources to do anything about it , the most senior chinese officials have acted more responsibly . 
in the space of a month after the adoption of the plan , new environmental taxes on cars , petrol and wood products were imposed : china uses market mechanisms to resolve its environmental problems and those of the world . 
but the pressures on local government officials to create economic growth and jobs will be enormous . 
they will be very tempted to say that if america is not capable of producing way to protect our planet , how can we ? 
to translate that vision into action , the chinese government will need strong policies , particularly significant increases taxes on the environment . 
while china became a market economy , it has developed some problems that are the scourge of developed countries : specific interests concealing personal interests under a mask of market ideology . 
some will trickle-down economics : do not worry for the poor , eventually everybody will benefit from the growth . 
and others will oppose competition policy and strong corporate governance laws : let darwinism operate its wonders . 
growth arguments will be advanced to counter strong social and environmental policies : for example , raise taxes on gasoline will kill our nascent auto industry . 
such allegedly pro-growth policies would not only to provide growth , they would threaten the entire vision of the future of china . 
there is only one way to prevent this : open discussion of economic policies in order to expose fallacies and provide the means to implement creative solutions for the many challenges facing china today . 
george w. bush has shown it is dangerous to abuse the secrecy and restrict the decision-making to a narrow circle of sycophants . 
most people outside china do not realise how its leaders , by contrast , have engaged in extensive deliberations and extensive consultations ( even with foreigners ) as they strive to solve the enormous problem they face . 
market economies are not self-regulating . 
they cannot simply be left on autopilot , especially if one wants to ensure that their profits are widely shared . 
but managing a market economy is not easy . 
it is a balancing act that must constantly respond to economic changes . 
china 's 11th five-year plan provides a roadmap in this direction . 
the world watches , full of hope and fear , as the lives of 1,3 billion people continue to be processed . 
