they must unite to others , as in the case of the european union , asean or mercosur , and increasingly rely on international institutions like the united nations , the world bank and the world trade organisation . 
such a view is risky . 
indeed , when you look closely , it is suspect , or simply wrong . 
the nation state , with its strengths and weaknesses , is alive and well . 
to begin with its strengths , the nation-state remains the only political space which manages to the constitution of freedom . 
the democratic credentials of organizations like the eu are dubious , and entirely absent in the case of the united nations and other global institutions . 
moreover , despite the frequent search of new identities , european , latin american or other , and despite many references to a new cosmopolitanism , or even a " world civil society , " most people feel at home in their own country , the nation state of which they are citizens . 
migration is generally led to other countries . 
many countries are currently debating the integration of migrants . 
what does it take to be british , german or american ? 
such debates on immigration make sense that if we recognize that citizenship is defined by and for the nations . 
this is , for most people , the positive side of the nation-state . 
the nation state has been for more than two centuries , and continues to be the reference of belonging and civic involvement for most of human beings . 
this is the context in which we see our freedoms protected or destroyed . 
the countries released of communism in 1989 have certainly felt that restore national sovereignty and recovering freedom were closely linked . 
yet there is , and always has been , another , uglier face of the nation-state : nationalism . 
the nationalist impulse can be aggressive or defensive , directed against the other or inward-looking . 
in both cases , it corrupts any attempt to create an international community of open societies . 
this was the problem in iraq : a nation state had become a troublemaker in the region and beyond . 
more recently , a less violent but equally worrying phenomenon has gained ground , the revival of national protectionism . 
the doha round of trade negotiations is stalled because developed countries refuse to open their markets to cheaper products from developing countries , which in turn are trying to protect their industries . 
many would prefer privileged relationships to open trade . 
in this area , the eu has often been helpful either . 
but today , the nationalist virus has infected the european union . 
france , spain and poland have tried to keep major industries firmly in " national hands . " 
suddenly , the single european market is forgotten , and a return to fragmented markets is taking root . 
consider , for example , the " directives on services " of the european commission . 
although freedom of movement for workers is one of the " four freedoms " of the single market , many eu countries are trying to protect their domestic labor markets by suspending this freedom as long as possible . 
germany , in particular , argues that the high unemployment resulting from the reunification in 1990 requires it to close its labour market for the new member states . 
such trends are dangerous . 
historically , protectionism has often led to economic conflict , which can quickly turn into more serious clashes . 
the signs are not good , even in europe . 
a recent summit of eu leaders to subject the energy policy -- area where cooperation is not only very desirable , but necessary . 
yet even german chancellor angela merkel , clearly pro-european , went to the meeting with the explicit intention to put a brake on the creation of other european powers in this area . 
the russian-german agreement to build a gas pipeline bypassing poland and lithuania , with the former chancellor gerhard schröder leading , has already contributed to the deterioration of relations between poland and germany , to say nothing of european cooperation . 
for a time , the pendulum of public opinion may have swung too far to the nation state and its role . 
this is one of the reasons why so many people have felt estranged from their political leaders . 
but it would be unfortunate , and even dangerous , that the pendulum back towards nationalism to the old . 
nation states are welcome , they are important elements of a liberal world order . 
but they must be open to cooperation and coordination with the others . 
we need to resist the birth of a trend that recalls the events of the early years of the 20th century , trend that was to lead to a global disaster . 
