islamist movements and the democratic paradox 
the wave of anger across the arab world after the publication in denmark , a few months ago , of cartoons depicting the prophet muhammad , the victory of hamas in palestine and the increasing radicalization of the iranian regime are " political islam " a fundamental problem on the international stage . 
but there can be no a single answer all the questions that arise . 
we need to abandon the idea that there is a monolithic islamist movement . 
political islam has different forms that have emerged as the main alternative to secular arab nationalist regimes whose legitimacy , based on the national liberation struggle , has disappeared due to their inability to solve the economic and social problems , establish the rule of law , and ensure the freedoms . 
in palestine , for example , the islamists have prevailed on fatah because of years of bad governance under the harsh conditions spawned by israeli occupation . 
for a long time , america and europe share an atavistic fear of the " islamic alternative " to the leaders secular nationalists like those of fatah and defend the status quo . 
but monarchs and secular dictators of the arab world have crushed any opposition , mosques , the only place in the shelter which the political commitment was possible . 
today , political islam can no longer be content , because we cannot build democracy in driving underground parties that have a strong social basis . this is what has tragically demonstrated in algeria 15 years ago . 
the only alternative to authoritarianism is to achieve a transition that allows islamists to participate in political life , while encouraging them to accept unequivocally the democratic rules of the game . 
in many countries , more or less conservative islamist parties are prepared to play the game . 
it is no coincidence if they are represented in the parliaments of all the countries that have committed political reforms , including lebanon , where hezbollah is part of a democratically elected government , jordan and morocco . 
in egypt , the muslim brotherhood have become a force to be reckoned with in parliament , despite the limits imposed on the participation of islamist groups in last year 's elections . 
in iraq , free elections have revealed the enormous influence of islamist currents . 
in turkey , the democratic transition brought to power an islamist party , the justice and development party . 
under his leadership , the turkish government has taken various important democratic reforms and began negotiations on the admission of turkey in the eu . 
islamist parties have nothing to do with al qaeda , even though some of the most conservative among them have ideological positions closer . 
the risk of a political transition that may lead to the victory of islamist parties is a democratic paradox that europe and the us must accept if they want to promote a political move that encompasses all political sensitivities - in other words the polar opposite of the imposition of democracy as it has in iraq , under occupation of foreign troops . 
one of the most negative consequences of the intervention in iraq was to reinforce the notion of a " clash of civilizations " between the west and islam which creates a climate conducive to islamist movements . 
the muslim world has made political reforms well before the " war against terrorism " and reformists were not waiting for the eu to become political clout to act . 
these movements were not created in the us or europe after the september 11 , and they do not expect a signal or help them to act . 
the success of muslim moderates could nevertheless to depend on the attitude of the eu and the us to them . 
it is not necessary to show that democracy is the best path for palestinians if they want to achieve their state . 
this depends largely on the new government of hamas , its transformation into a democratic strength , respects the rule of law , democracy and international law . 
but it also depends on israel and the international community , which must do everything in their power to encourage the emergence of a future palestinian state with jerusalem as its capital . 
supporting palestinian democratization does not prevent the international community to demand that hamas give up entirely on terrorism , to demilitarise , respect the palestinian constitution , and acknowledge the existence of israel . 
but this does not mean that we need to impose sanctions on the palestinian people , after he has spoken democratically . 
if we want to strengthen the recent palestinian democracy , it would be a terrible mistake that would have a negative impact in other arab countries seeking to reform . 
in the same way , recognise the right of non-violent islamists to participate in the political life does not mean the renunciation of the political and ideological struggle to overcome the ultra-conservative views and sometimes totalitarian society . 
combating racism , defend tolerance and respect the religious sentiments of others does not mean to question the freedom of the press or to accept the censorship that call for the islamists , even if real religious sentiments are injured , as in the case of the danish caricatures . 
islamist conceptions of society that violate individual rights must be rebutted politically . 
this political challenge is one of the paradoxes of democracy , because it allows all the ideas to compete freely with each other . 
political islam is a risk , but you cannot reduce that drafting a proper strategy , adapted to the case by case , and that goes in the direction of democracy , but not in denouncing the result of a democratic choice . 
