the abandonment of the resolutions of lisbon 
as soon as he takes office at the post of president of the european commission , durao barroso - former prime minister of portugal - should devote urgent to restoring order and focus to the economic policies of the european union . 
the thickest file on the expected is that of the resolutions of lisbon , an ambitious programme approved in 2000 by the heads of state and government of the european union with the aim of making the union " the most competitive and dynamic economy " as soon as 2010 . 
the main economic fields are covered : innovation and entrepreneurship , the reform of social systems and social inclusion , skills and employment , equality of the sexes at work , the liberalisation of labour markets and goods and sustainable development . 
it is certain that these are worthy goals , to be sure , but they belong intrinsically to the sphere of national political decisions . 
indeed , according to the european treaties , the union has no authority to enact legislation and policy in these areas , nor the power to enforce them . 
however , the council of europe , encouraged by the european commission , invented a new policy approach - called " open coordination " - to be able to affect these areas . 
open coordination entails the determination of common objectives at european union level , voluntary compliance by the member states and internal control of results in the council of europe . 
of course , open coordination has failed to deliver on its promises . 
in addition , the illusion that the council of europe can somehow call growth and productivity has provided a diversion to national politicians who do not want to make the promotion at the national level of unpopular decisions . 
thus , i suggest to mr barroso , in a prime time , get rid of the resolutions of lisbon . 
this is the only thing to do to make clear that national responsibilities remain in the hands of national politicians on economic performance . 
this brings me to macro-economic coordination at european union level . 
the maastricht treaty envisaged a simple policy framework for economic and monetary union . 
monetary policy was centralized and entrusted to an independent central bank , while fiscal policy was left to the member states . 
national governments were subject to the dual constraint - according to the procedure of control excessive deficits - aimed at preventing the fiscal deficits of more than 3 % of gdp and budget deficits of more than 60 % of gdp ( or at least around this value ) . 
subsequently , the stability and growth pact added an additional criterion , in the medium term , for that national budgets are balanced or " almost " . 
essentially , this aimed to prevent irresponsible budgetary policies after the launch of the euro , while leaving enough space to cyclical oscillations deficits in the limit of 3 % . 
the credibility of this arsenal was badly damaged by the november 2003 public controversy between the commission and the ecofin council on the application of the control procedure budget deficits to france and germany . 
this does not mean that it should be abandoned . 
on the contrary , a common external constraint on fiscal behavior is necessary for a joint safeguard against an unsustainable accumulation of public debt , which could affect financial stability and inflation across the european union - an increased risk by the impact of ageing populations on pension systems . 
such a constraint also provides a welcome anchor for domestic decision-making in member states with weaker political systems . 
but the system needs to be reviewed . 
i would not listen to those who defend the exclusion of investment from fiscal deficits : this would only offer new incentives for creative accounting and unsustainable accumulation of debt . 
instead , the focus should be on the viability of the debt rather than on the annual deficits . 
the debt criterion , for example , could be accompanied by a limit on the ( trend ) growth rate of public spending , which would be kept below the nominal gdp . 
the power of the commission to launch the movement when there is a risk of excessive deficits should be strengthened - unless , of course , the commission never again forgets that the follow-up of national policies is a task that requires a certain sense policy and cannot be left to accountants and lawyers . 
finally , we must make european integration the main priority for which the union has a powerful legal instrument to force the opening up of markets and strengthen competition . 
the best therapy for boosting growth must be both direct , by increasing competitive pressure , and indirect , by triggering the necessary adaptation national policies on employment , social welfare and education . 
this is a long haul . 
state aid to ailing companies remain ambiguous and common rules designed to ensure the free movement of goods and services are not fully respected by the member states - the public markets and energy are the best examples . 
moreover , most markets of services - the trade securities , wholesale and retail distribution , business services , and local public services - remain protected competition and the regulation of free trade . 
the evidence is there that show that these distortions in the market for services , which represents two thirds of gdp are responsible for the bulk of the eu 's productivity gap with the united states . 
in recent years , the council of europe has not paid enough attention to these tasks , which require full and continuing commitment on the part of the member states to transpose and implement the european directives . 
all too often , the commission has promoted the introduction of new legislation and the creation of new spending programs rather than effective management of what is already in place . 
thus , mr barroso should forget the platitudes of the lisbon agenda and concentrate instead on the actual implementation of the single market and bring order to the fiscal policies of member states . 
it must be left to local governments take responsibility for the economic performance of their country . 
the emotional clash of civilisations 
throughout the so-called " war against terrorism , " the concept of " shock of civilization " between islam and the west has usually been excluded as politically incorrect and intellectually wrongheaded . 
the most common interpretation to place is that the world has entered a new era of conflict " within " particular civilization , namely islam , with fundamentalist muslims as much in war against moderates as against the west . 
the strategic conclusion derived from such an analysis was clear , ambitious and easily summarized : democratization . 
if the absence of democracy in the islamic world was the problem , bringing democracy to the " big " middle east would be the solution , and it was the historical duty of the united states , as the most powerful and moral nation , to provide the necessary change . 
the status quo was untenable . 
implementing democracy , with or without regime change , was the only alternative to chaos and the rise of fundamentalism . 
today , iraq may be on the brink of civil war between shiites and sunnis . 
iran , ruled by a new and more radical president , irresistibly , is heading towards obtaining a nuclear capability . 
a free electoral process brought hamas to power in palestine , and the unfortunate episode of the danish newspaper cartoons illustrated the almost combustible nature of relations between islam and the west . 
all these developments are paving the way to new interpretations . 
rather than a " clash of civilizations , " we could be facing many levels of conflict , which interact with them so that they increase global instability . 
indeed , it appears that the world is witnessing a triple conflict . 
there is a division within islam , which , if the violence in iraq is spreading to neighbouring countries , risk provoking regional destabilization . 
there is also a clash that should not be regarded as between islam and the west , but between the secular world and a growing religious world . 
in an even deeper and atavistic level , there is an emotional conflict between a culture of fear and a culture of humiliation . 
this would be a gross oversimplification to speak , as some do , a clash between civilization and barbarism . 
in fact , we are facing a widening divide on the role of religion , which runs between the west ( with the united states in the role of the complicated exception ) and most of the rest of the world ( the most notable exception being china ) , particularly the islamic world . 
the gap reflects how religion defines an individual 's identity within a society . 
at a time when religion is becoming increasingly important elsewhere , we europeans have largely forgotten our past religious ( violent and intolerant ) , and have difficulty understanding the role that religion can play in the daily lives of other people . 
in some ways , " they " are our own buried past and , in a combination of ignorance , prejudice , and by all , fear , " we " are afraid that " they " could define our future . 
we live in a secular world , where freedom of expression can easily turn into insensitive and irresponsible mockery , while others see religion as their supreme goal , if not their last hope . 
they have tried everything , from nationalism to regionalism , from communism to capitalism . 
since everything has failed , why not try god ? 
globalization may not have created these levels of conflicts , but it has accelerated them by making the differences more visible and palpable . 
in our globalized age , we have lost the privilege , and paradoxically , virtue , ignorance . 
we all see how others feel and react , but without the historical and cultural instruments necessary to decipher these responses . 
globalization has paved the way to a world dominated by the dictatorship of emotions and ignorance . 
this emotional clash is exacerbated in the case of islam . 
in the arab world , in particular , islam is dominated by a culture of humiliation felt by the people and nations who regard themselves as the main losers , the worst victims , of a new international system and unfair . 
from this point of view , the israeli-palestinian conflict is exemplary . 
it has become an obsession . 
this is not so much that arabs and muslims really care about the palestinians . 
on the contrary , the islamic world has left the palestinians without real support for decades . 
in reality , for them the conflict has come to symbolize the anachronistic perpetuation of an unfair colonial order , to represent their political malaise , and to embody the impossibility that they perceive to be masters of their fate . 
in arab eyes ( and some other muslims ) , the strength and resilience of israel is a direct consequence of their own weakness , divisions , and corruption . 
the majority of arabs may not support al-qaeda , but they do not oppose all their heart . 
instead , there is the temptation to treat osama bin laden as a kind of violent robin hood , whose actions , officially unforgivable , helped them recover a sense of arab pride and dignity . 
this is , perhaps , is the true clash of civilizations : the emotional conflict between the european culture of fear and the culture of the humiliation muslim , and more particularly arabic . 
it would be dangerous to underestimate the depth of so wide an emotional divide , and to recognize its existence is the first step to overcoming it . 
but it will be difficult , because transcend the emotional clash of civilizations presupposes an opening to the " other " that none of the two sides is perhaps ready to consider . 
globalisation and anti-americanism 
anti-american sentiments are everywhere in the world . 
american democrats say that president bush 's policies have damaged the attractiveness of america . 
republicans respond that america is bound to be resented the fact of its size and its association with globalisation . 
according to them , anti-americanism will persist because some people see america as a cultural threat . 
for my part , i think that these positions lack historical perspective . 
contrary to conventional wisdom , globalization is not a factor and homogenisation of americanization the cultures of the world . 
although the united states is at the forefront of the current information revolution , which enables us to develop the similarities of social and cultural habits ( such as television viewing or the use of the internet ) , which are attributed to americanization , even if the correlation is not causation . 
to understand why , imagine a country that introduced computers and communication with speed in a world where america did not exist . 
you would still expect to social and cultural changes of the importance of such modernization . 
of course , because of the existence of the us and their presence at the vanguard of the information revolution , there is a degree of americanization , which will diminish probably during the twenty-first century thanks to the technological penetration and modernisation of local cultures at their own pace . 
historical proof that globalization does not necessarily mean homogenisation lies in japan , a country that deliberately isolated from the rest of the world when the first waves of globalization . 
in the middle of the nineteenth century , japan became the first asian country to embrace globalization , and to borrow with success in the rest of the world without losing its uniqueness . 
during the meiji restoration , japan has sought everywhere the tools and innovations that would allow it to become a major power rather than a victim of western imperialism . 
it sent his youth studying in western societies . 
its delegations scoured the world looking for scientific innovations , technology , and industry . 
in the political field , meiji reformers were very aware of the philosophy and institutions , but they chose to turn to the german model because they were deemed more suitable to a country run by an emperor . 
the lesson that japan gives the rest of the world is not only to the fact that an asian country can be competitive , but that after a century and a half of globalization , it is possible to adapt while preserving a unique culture . 
above all , the image of america as a factor homogenisation reflects a mistakenly static view of cultures . 
the efforts to show local cultures as unchanging often reflect reactionary political strategies rather than a description of the reality . 
