the economy of fear 
the global economy seems to be walking on water , a shrug of the shoulders of rising oil prices , the political paralysis in europe , the unsustainable deficit of the united states and the record prices of real estate . 
is it because , as would have us believe the leaders of the g8 , investors are optimistic , confident in the direction given to the world economy by their leaders ? 
or are we being governed by a pathology of fear , fed by events such as the recent terrorist attacks in london , which maintains long-term interest rates low , masking a host of simmering problems ? 
the role of long-term interest rates , extremely low ( after adjustment for inflation ) , who hides a multitude of weaknesses in the global economy is all too apparent . 
rising house prices around the world supports the demand in many countries , and , according to a recent study of the international monetary fund , the interest rates falling continues explain two-thirds or more of the global price rise . 
europe has benefited less , but its economies would be far worse if long-term interest rates climbed back to their average it was 25 years ago . 
similarly , latin america has been booming in recent years , despite the weight of debt and a political reform mixed . 
the weak long-term interest rates have allowed the region to manage its debt , while the demand has helped push up the price of exports of commodities in the region . 
why the surge in oil prices has not only put the world to its knees , as was so often the case in the past ? 
once again , the answer lies in the low interest rates . 
usually , a sharp rise in oil prices quickly translates into higher inflation expectations , followed by rising interest rates at all maturities . 
but this time the us federal reserve keeps hiking its short-term lending rate to control inflation and long-term interest rates , which are far more important , have declined , as if by magic . 
indeed , america is the single biggest beneficiary of this low interest rates , where everyone borrows money as if soon there would be more nowhere . 
homeowners , backed by the rise of home prices , mounting debts . 
the federal government has thrown fiscal prudence out the window . 
the country as a whole is absorbing an incredible three-quarters of global savings . 
but , as long as interest rates remain low and high growth , americans can laugh at those predictions that their excesses fruit of ruin . 
but if the weak long-term interest rates help so many economies walk on water , why are rates so low and this situation will it continue ? 
perhaps the situation is far more fragile than many politicians would have us believe . 
people feel perhaps less , not more , security about their long-term future , either because they fear terrorism , a global pandemic , or a severe rash of financial crises . 
i am not saying that investors are hysterical , but simply that they have become a little more concerned about the long-term outlook . 
therefore , they are throwing themselves on the actions and borrowing securities they receive , rightly or wrongly , as safe . 
we lack other explanations . 
it is certain that emerging markets have been in an unusual savings spree , rebuilding reserves and improving their balance sheets , but nobody expects that to continue indefinitely . 
even the director of the us federal reserve , alan greenspan , the oracle of delphi on interest rates , says about the current situation that it is a " conundrum . " 
history suggests that the technology boom has yet to play its role , and with productivity gains americans prepared to irradiating the world , raising the rate of growth everywhere . 
usually , a rapid global growth translates into higher interest rate for the long term , unless , of course , at the bottom , people have become worried . 
suppose that investors are worried about the possibility of disaster in the five to ten years . 
( according to experts on nuclear terrorism and pandemics , the risk is real . ) 
suppose that investors believe that growth will probably continue to be strong , but that maybe -- just maybe -- the situation will fall apart . 
in this case , it is entirely possible to low interest rates co-exist with strong growth . 
it is true that some economists point to the happy days of the 1950s and early 1960s , when europe , the united states and japan prospered , but interest rates generally remained well below the rate of economic growth . 
this time representing the golden age of global growth , why worry if we live the same phenomenon today ? 
what the optimists forget is that these years were paradise also a period of uncertainty . 
many were those who feared , in reality , the outbreak of world war iii , and rightly so , according to many historians . 
back then , the specter of the apocalypse helped keep the loans at a rate affordable . 
fortunately , the worst fears of investors are not carried out , and we can only hope today the same thing . 
