political upheaval in israel 
israeli politics is experiencing its most dramatic changes in 30 years . 
the realignment of parties and leaders is particularly remarkable because the unexpected nature of recent events in date : ariel sharon 's decision to leave the likud , the defeat of shimon peres as leader of the labour party and the withdrawal of labour sharon 's grand coalition government . 
it is more important to comprehend the significance of these changes for the future of israel , the region , and the arab-israeli conflict . 
in short , israel 's political system is approaching the end of its second era . 
the independence in 1948 until 1977 , the labour party has dominated , before giving way to an opposition coalition of conservative , nationalist , and centrist parties allies in the likud bloc . 
since then , the two parties have alternated in power , sometimes in grand coalitions and sometimes in partnership with smaller parties . 
on the surface , the rivalry between the parties has been between " left " and " right , " or " hawks " and " doves . " 
the truth , of course , is more complex . 
the classes and the economic problems , in the shadow of more existential concerns , such as the physical security and the continued existence of the state , have played a much less important role in israel than in other societies . 
here , the political divide could be defined as " optimists " and " pessimistic " . 
the first , labour , believed that one day a force would emerge among arabs and palestinians ready to make peace on a reasonable basis , while the latter , likud , were more cautious . 
for years , the discussion has remained an abstraction , a debate over what might happen in the future , until the oslo accords with the plo in 1993 put to the test the rival visions . 
since 2000 , when plo leader yasser arafat rejected a political agreement and instead launched a five-year war of terrorism , there is little optimistic . 
the subsequent intellectual realignment in israel has given birth to a new national consensus . 
it is now widely accepted that , as the left has always insisted , israel should be ready to withdraw from the west bank and gaza strip and to accept the existence of a palestinian state in exchange for real peace . 
but it is also accepted that , as the right has always maintained , there is no partner really ready to make peace . 
in this context , sharon has won two landslide election victories as a radical while a moderate policy , including a full withdrawal from the gaza strip . 
this is where israel today , facing a political upheaval fueled by two new elements . 
first , sharon moved the likud in the centre , and made the hegemonic party , while destroying all the stereotypes about his personality , his methods and his vision of the world . 
yet this is for the same reason that a lot of likud members consider sharon , who helped found the party , as a traitor . 
sharon now needs to institutionalize his reforms , even if it must establish another party to this . 
secondly , the labour party has demonstrated its bankruptcy policy , because its only conceivable leader was a shimon peres age 82 and its anachronistic optimism of dove was ridiculed . 
as a result , and thanks to a low turnout in the elections , the party primaries have been won by amir peretz , an outsider and populist who wants to revitalize the labour party in highlighting the social and economic problems , which means the withdrawal of the national unity coalition with likud . 
although it should form a new party , sharon will probably win the next election , he has planned for february . 
peretz 's strategy may draw voters from other parties of the left , but labor will surely lose centrist voters ( and those for whom national security is a priority ) to sharon . 
paradoxically , all this will have a great deal in principle and perhaps very modest in practice . 
while sharon enjoying a strong public support for a moderate policy , israel will be more ready than ever to reach an agreement with the palestinians , syria , and the arab world in general in order to find a comprehensive diplomatic solution to the conflict . 
yet , given the chaos and the paralysis that increasingly characterize palestinian politics , this opportunity will not be seized . 
the growing power of hamas , which openly proclaims its strategy to increase the acts of terrorism and destroying israel , reinforces that this trend . 
the same can be said of syria , whose hardline government turns to a dangerously adventurous militancy . 
sharon might decide on partial withdrawals and dismantling of settlements in the west bank . 
but it is now widely accepted that such changes are a response to dim prospects of real progress toward peace . 
clinging to the territories as a bargaining chip makes less sense if there is no one with whom to haggle . 
instead , israel will continue to prioritize its own security , strengthening its defenses against terrorism and consolidating its control over the relatively small portions of the west bank that it intends to claim as part of a possible diplomatic settlement . 
a byproduct of this strategy , combined with the palestinian attacks , sympathy has been growing international against israel . 
this phenomenon could continue if the current political realignment has occurred , enabling sharon to win its programme the centre and even the moderate left . 
nothing is assured , of course . 
benjamin netanyahu , who remains popular , may very well become a powerful rival to his right , and peretz might of the labour party into a serious contender to his left . 
in any case , the national consensus has changed , shaking all convictions in israeli politics . 
the february elections will put these assumptions to their toughest test in decades . 
