fdi can bring many benefits , it has also sometimes costs . 
in the 1970s , when the transnational corporations ( tnc 's ) that such investment have begun to point out , many governments have believed that the costs of fdi outweighed their profits and so they controlled . 
the pendulum , held by developed countries , began to swing in the 1980s . 
once viewed as part of the problem , fdi became part of the solution to economic growth and development . 
nothing illustrates that better than changes in national fdi regimes . 
as reports the united nations conference on trade and development , among the 2 156 changes that took place between 1991 and 2004 , 93 % were to create a more hospitable environment for tnc 's . 
but the risk that the pendulum to swing back is real , leading to a reversal of this liberalisation process . 
fdi in developed countries ( and increasingly in emerging markets ) often takes the form of cross-border mergers and acquisitions . 
the resistance to such steps is becoming more frequent when they involve companies that politicians regard as " national champions " or that play a role in national security , economic development or cultural identity . 
the growing involvement of private equity firms in the activities of mergers and acquisitions raises other controversies , because such transactions are typically considered purely speculative . 
on behalf of " economic patriotism , " security and other considerations , resistance to mergers and acquisitions is codified in a growing number of countries . 
for example , a united states senate committee recently tried to block the project liberalization of foreign takeover rules for the airlines , and europe has put in place more restrictive takeover laws . 
in addition , governments are applying more strictly existing regulatory provisions concerning the control of takeovers by foreign firms . 
this response is linked to a defensive reaction to the growing role of tnc 's from emerging markets , " small news . " 
